<DOC><DOCNO> AP880901-0266 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1117EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-Microsoft     09-01 0148</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Microsoft,0155</SECOND><HEAD>Microsoft To Help Develop Sound And Graphics Standard For PCs</HEAD><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Microsoft Corp. says it has agreed with NVPhilips of the Netherlands and Sony Corp. of Japan to add sound andgraphics to the CD ROM format developed for personal computers.   The CD ROM format was developed by Philips and Sony. It standsfor compact disk, read-only memory. The format uses compact disksto record vast amounts of text and pictures.   But CD ROM's graphics ability is limited to line drawings.   Sony and Phillips also developed another system, CD-I, forcompact disk-interactive, that has sound and much liveliergraphics. But it won't work on personal computers.   Microsoft spokesman Collins Hemingway said the aim of theresearch is to devise a standard and write PC software that allowsprogrammers to create sound and graphics playable on personalcomputers as well as CD-I equipment.</TEXT></DOC>